  "prompt": "I am repairing a soft steel chair by arc welding and keep burning holes in the metal, what can I do to make a strong joint?",
  "response": "The issue you're facing \u2013 burning holes in soft steel during arc welding \u2013 can be frustrating, but there are several strategies you can implement to create strong joints without damaging the material:\n\n1. **Control the Heat**: Using too much heat is the primary reason for burning holes in thinner metals. Try lowering the current on your welding machine. Smaller electrodes create less heat and can help avoid burning through the material.\n\n2. **Movement and Technique**: Adjust your welding technique. Move the electrode more quickly to avoid concentrating too much heat in one spot. Consider using a stitching technique or short, intermittent welds, especially if welding in tight spots. You might also try practicing on scrap metal first to perfect your technique.\n\n3. **Use Filler Material**: Sometimes using filler material can help fill gaps and build up the welded area without overheating the surrounding metal. This can reinforce the joint and mitigate burning holes.\n\n4. **Pre-Weld Preparation**:\n    - **Cleanliness**: Ensure the metal surfaces are clean before you begin welding. Dirt, grease, and oxides can cause defects in your weld and excessive heat buildup.\n    - **Fit-Up**: Ensure good fit-up of the parts to be welded, with minimal gaps.\n\n5. **Try Pulse Welding**: Some welding machines have a pulse feature that can help control heat input by cycling the current on and off rapidly.\n\n6. **Welding Technique Adjustments**:\n    - For thinner metals, you might benefit from using techniques such as the \"back-step\" method, where you weld small sections going back over previously welded areas.\n    - \"Butter\" the edges by running the arc over the joint without adding filler material can help to preheat and stabilize the area before making the actual welds.\n\n7. **Use a Different Welding Process**: If arc welding continues to be problematic, consider switching to a different welding method better suited for thin metals, such as MIG or TIG welding. Both of these processes offer better control over heat input and can be easier on thinner materials.\n\nImproving these aspects should help you create strong weld joints without burning holes in the steel. Always remember to wear appropriate safety gear and follow safety protocols when welding.",
